Port uu_cp 0.8.0 to a NATIVE in-process brush builtin, like uu_cat/uu_sort, so
a `-b` box (and make/ninja recipes) run `cp` IN-PROCESS with NO forked
/usr/bin/cp. Two divergences from upstream, both local to vendor/uu_cp:

* Logical I/O: a new entry `cp(args, cwd, out, err)` runs on the builtin's
  worker thread writing the shell's logical OpenFile sinks, never the process's
  fd 1/2. uu_cp's verbose `println!` and uucore `show!`/`show_error!`/
  `show_warning!`/`eprintln!` are routed to thread-local buffers (CP_OUT/CP_ERR)
  + a deferred exit code (CP_EXIT) via crate-local `cp_out!`/`show*` macros that
  shadow the uucore originals; the entry drains them to out/err and surfaces the
  status (fatal CpError → its code, NotAllFilesCopied/CP_EXIT → 1). No
  process-global stdio, no process-global EXIT_CODE — parallel-safe. The
  standalone `#[uucore::main] uumain` bridge is retained for the binary path.
* Logical cwd: brush never chdir's the process, so the entry rewrites every
  relative path operand (and -t/--target-directory) against the shell's logical
  cwd (context.shell.working_dir()) before copy() — exactly find's approach.

CpBuiltin (src/brush.rs) is registered UNCONDITIONALLY (unlike the bundle-gated
coreutils): make recipes call cp constantly and forking /usr/bin/cp would escape
the box's logical cwd/I-O; the localization-cache hazard that gates the others
no longer applies (cp runs on its own thread; uucore's Fluent caches are
thread-local). Contract test gains in-process + logical-cwd cp cases (81 cases).
Fixes test_n2_rs case2/case4 and test_make_rs case2.

